'''Gelao''' ([[Endonym|autonym]]: '''Kl<U+00E1>o''', Chinese: '''<U+4EE1><U+4F6C>''' G<U+0113>l<U+01CE>o, Vietnamese: '''C<U+1EDD> Lao''') is a dialect cluster of [[Kra languages]] in the [[Tai<U+2013>Kadai languages|Tai<U+2013>Kadai language family]]. It is spoken by the [[Gelao people]] in [[southern China]] and [[northern Vietnam]]. Despite an ethnic population of 580,000 (2000 census), however, only a few thousand still speak the language. Estimates run from 3,000 in China by [[Li Jinfang|Li]] in 1999, of which 500 are monolinguals, to 7,900 by [[Jerold A. Edmondson|Edmonson]] in 2008. Edmondson (2002) estimates that the three Gelao varieties of Vietnam have only about 350 speakers altogether.

In 2009, a book allegedly written in a native Gelao script was found in [[Guizhou]], China.<ref>http://news.cultural-china.com/20090203171833.html</ref> It is not known whether this find is authentic.

==External relationships==
Like [[Buyang language|Buyang]], another [[Kra languages|Kra language]], Gelao contains many words which are likely to be [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] cognates.{{citation-needed|date=February 2013}} (''See [[Austro-Tai]]''.)

As noted by Li and Zhou,<ref name="tansuo"><U+674E><U+9526><U+82B3>/Li, Jinfang and <U+5468><U+56FD><U+708E>/Guoyan Zhou. <U+4EE1><U+592E><U+8BED><U+8A00><U+63A2><U+7D22>/Geyang yu yan tan suo. Beijing, China: <U+4E2D><U+592E><U+6C11><U+65CF><U+5927><U+5B66><U+51FA><U+7248><U+793E>/Zhong yang min zu da xue chu ban she, 1999.</ref> Gelao shares much vocabulary with the [[Hlai languages|Hlai]] and [[Ong Be language|Ong Be]] languages, suggesting contact with Pre-Hlai speakers before their migration to [[Hainan]].

==Demographics==
Zhang Jimin estimated a total of over 10,000 Gelao speakers in the early 1990s, while Li Jinfang places this number at 3,000 in 1999.<ref>http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=gio</ref> Jerold A. Edmondson's 2008 estimate is 7,900 speakers.<ref>Diller, Anthony, Jerry Edmondson, Yongxian Luo. (2008). ''The Tai<U+2013>Kadai Languages''. London [etc.]: Routledge. ISBN 978-0-7007-1457-5.</ref> This number is rapidly declining, as the Gelao are intermarrying with the neighboring [[Han people|Han]], [[Bouyei people|Bouyei]], and [[Miao people|Miao]]. Many Gelao speakers can also speak Bouyei, Zhuang, or Miao, and nearly all can speak local varieties of [[Chinese language|Chinese]]. Among Gelao-speaking families, most middle-age Gelao have very limited speaking abilities for Gelao, while much of the younger generation cannot even understand the most simple words and phrases.

The most endangered variety, Red Gelao of Vietnam, is spoken by only about 50 people. Many speakers have shifted to [[Southwestern Mandarin]] or [[Hmong language|Hmong]]. The Red Gelao people, who call themselves the ''va35 nt<U+026F>31'', send brides back and forth among the villages of Na Kh<U+00EA> and B<U+1EA1>ch <U+0110><U+00ED>ch (or B<U+00EC>ch <U+0110>ich) in [[Y<U+00EA>n Minh District]], [[H<U+00E0> Giang Province]], Vietnam and another village in Fanpo, [[Malipo County]], [[Yunnan]], China<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=161186</ref> (autonym: ''u33 wei55'') in order to ensure the continual survival of their ethnic group. Edmondson (1998) reports that there are also Red Gelao people in C<U+00E1>n T<U+00ED>, [[Qu<U+1EA3>n B<U+1EA1> District]] and T<U+00FA>ng S<U+00E1>n, [[Ho<U+00E0>ng Su Ph<U+00EC> District]]<ref>http://bienphong.com.vn/BaoBienPhong/32/352/352/20237/Net-dep-trong-dam-cuoi-cua-nguoi-Co-Lao/bbp.aspx</ref> who no longer speak any Gelao, and speak Hmong, Tay, or Vietnamese instead.<ref>http://sealang.net/sala/archives/pdf8/edmondson1998language.pdf</ref> However, the White Gelao of Ph<U+1ED1> La Village and S<U+00ED>nh L<U+1EE7>ng Village of D<U+1ED3>ng V<U+0103>n District still speak the White Gelao language.

The Mulao number 28,000 people, and are distributed in Majiang, Kaili, Huangping, Duyun, Weng'an, Fuquan, and other counties of southeastern Guizhou. The Mulao of Xuanwei and Jidong villages refer to themselves as the ''Mu'', in Longli village they call themselves ''qa24 <U+0263>o53''. The Mulao speak a variety of Gelao, and not the [[Mulam language|Mulam]] language of Guangxi, which is also called Mulao.

Zhou (2004) reports that there are no more than 6,000 Gelao speakers, making up only 1.2% of the total number of ethnic [[Gelao people]]. The following table, based on Zhou (2004:150-151), shows the number of Gelao speakers in each [[Counties of the People's Republic of China|county]] as of the 1990s. All counties are in [[Guizhou]] province unless specified otherwise.

