==Phonology==
Gelao has many [[uvular consonants|uvular]] and [[prenasalized consonant]]s.<ref name="krac">Edmondson, Jerold A. ''Kra or Kadai languages''. http://ling.uta.edu/~jerry/krac.pdf</ref> Many varieties also preserve [[consonant cluster]]s that have been lost in most other related languages. These consonant clusters, such as {{IPA|pl, bl, p<U+02B0>l, ml, mpl, vl, and kl}}, correspond regularly with consonants in Lachi, Mulao, Qabiao (Pubiao), Buyang, and various Kam<U+2013>Tai languages. Gelao also shares many phonological features with [[Bouyei language|Bouyei]] and other neighboring non-Kra languages.

Many Gelao varieties have a total of six tones, including two level tones (''{{IPA|<U+02E7>}}'' and ''{{IPA|<U+02E5>}}''), two rising tones (''{{IPA|<U+02E9><U+02E7>}}'' and ''{{IPA|<U+02E7><U+02E5>}}''), and two falling tones (''{{IPA|<U+02E7><U+02E9>}}'' and ''{{IPA|<U+02E5><U+02E7>}}'').{{fix|text=These do not match the tones in the autonyms and in the grammar section}}

Sound correspondences between the [[Liuzhi]] (<U+516D><U+679D>) and [[Zhenfeng County|Zhenfeng]] (<U+8D1E><U+4E30>) varieties include:<ref name="tansuo"/>

[Liuzhi : Zhenfeng]

*{{IPA|pl}} : {{IPA|pj}}
*{{IPA|p<U+02B0>l}} : {{IPA|p}}
*{{IPA|ml}} : {{IPA|m}}
*{{IPA|mp}} : {{IPA|m}}
*{{IPA|nt<U+0255>}} : {{IPA|<U+0272>}} or {{IPA|n<U+02B2>}}
*{{IPA|<U+014B>k}} : {{IPA|<U+014B>}} or {{IPA|k}}

==Grammar==
Like all of its surrounding languages, Gelao is a [[head-first]], [[Subject<U+2013>verb<U+2013>object|SVO]] language. Like [[Buyang language|Buyang]], one unusual feature of Gelao is that negatives usually come at the end of a sentence. [[Reduplication]] is very common and is used for diminutive or repetitive purposes.<ref name="krac"/> Other common features include the use of serial verb constructions and compound nouns. Although numerals and [[classifier]]s precede nouns, adjectives (including [[demonstrative]]s) always follow the noun. Function words, such as [[preposition]]s and auxiliary words, are often derived from verbs.

Like [[Buyang language|Buyang]] and [[Dong language|Dong]], Gelao retains many prefixes that have been lost in most other [[Tai<U+2013>Kadai languages]]. Zhang (1993:300) notes that the Moji (<U+78E8><U+57FA>) Longlin variant makes especially extensive use of prefixing syllables before nouns, verbs, and adjectives.<ref name="zhang"><U+5F20><U+6E08><U+6C11>/Zhang, Jimin. <U+4EE1><U+4F6C><U+8BED><U+7814><U+7A76>/Gelao yu yan jiu (A Study of Gelao). <U+8D35><U+9633><U+5E02>/Guiyang, China: <U+8D35><U+5DDE><U+6C11><U+65CF><U+51FA><U+7248><U+793E>/Guizhou min zu chu ban she, 1993.</ref> These prefixes are especially important for reconstruction purposes.

Many words in Gelao are derived from vernacular [[Southwest Mandarin]] Chinese. These loanwords are often used interchangeably with native Gelao words. There is also a highly rich system of classifiers.

Gelao also has a rich set of pronouns not attested in other Tai<U+2013>Kadai languages.<ref name="krac"/> There are also pronouns referring to one's household in particular. The following are pronouns from [[Pingba]] Gelao.<ref name="zhang"/>

*({{IPA|su<U+02E7>}}) {{IPA|i<U+02E6><U+02E8>}} <U+2013> I
*({{IPA|su<U+02E7>}}) {{IPA|mu<U+02E8><U+02E9>}} - you
*({{IPA|su<U+02E7>}}) {{IPA|u<U+02E6><U+02E8>}} - he, she, it
*({{IPA|su<U+02E7>}}) {{IPA|ta<U+02E7>}} - we
*({{IPA|su<U+02E7>}}) {{IPA|sa<U+02E7>}} - you all
*{{IPA|p<U+0259><U+02E6><U+02E8>nu<U+02E6><U+02E8>}} - they
*{{IPA|qa<U+02E7>/a<U+02E7> qei<U+02E6><U+02E8>}} - my household
*{{IPA|qa<U+02E7>/a<U+02E7> mu<U+02E8><U+02E9>}} - your household
*{{IPA|qa<U+02E7>/a<U+02E5> qu<U+02E6><U+02E8>}} - his/her household

Pingba Gelao numerals are given below. Note the similarities with the [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] numeral system.

